Clearly not. The creature simply whistled and tried to charge straight at Thassalin. Fortunately, despite its size, it was agile enough to dodge, but Nyssi couldn't help but scream when she nearly lost grip on its overly smooth scales.
" HOW DO WE KILL THEM? ", cried Nyssi.
"AIM FOR THEIR HEADS!"
"IT'S NOT GOING TO BE EASY!"
Thassalin exhaled, then circled around to get closer to the mountain he called his home. The black beast followed, somewhat panicked when a bolt of fire struck it from behind. The creature had not noticed that it was no longer alone. Its panic grew when Thassalin slowed down, then violently struck it on the head with his tail, diverting its course.
Grumbling and whistling, the creature gained altitude and spat into the air. Suddenly, everything turned black, as if the monster was sucking the light from the sky and replacing it with a permanent cloud of eternal night.
With no visibility left, Thassalin tried to retreat, but brushed against the tree tops before crashing into the clearing. As if she had known exactly where he had fallen, the creature charged straight at him, dragging the dark cloud behind her.
"Kayel!" shouted Tenuk as he pulled himself out of the cloud and began flying in circles to try to spot Nyssi and Thassalin below in the darkness. "What are we doing, Kayel? Kayel...? Kayel, where are you?"
Down below, Nyssi struggled to her feet. She was sure she had broken something, but her strange, unnatural healing powers had already started taking effect. One could not say the same for Thassalin, who was lying on a mound, leaning against the only tree that had not bent under his weight. Nyssi did her best to try to reach Thassalin, but she could not see two meters ahead of her. Everything was plunged into darkness, swallowed by impious shadows. And within these shadows, something was howling.
A terrible, club-like tail came crashing down beside Nyssi, knocking her backward. She noticed, however, that the tail was swaying, not aiming at her. The creature, from what Nyssi could see and hear, was growling and scratching at the shadows it had created. Something was teleporting through the darkness, striking the monster and disorienting it.
A gunshot rang out suddenly, and the monster collapsed in silence, lifeless. The darkness surrounding them dissipated, revealing what had happened. Standing over the creature was Kayel, holding the rifle and breathing heavily.
"C'est... the most bizarre shadow leap I've ever made... Thanto kat'olon...", panted Kayel. His eyes glowed with a black light, and a dark energy coursed through his body. However, as he spoke, the organic plating of Kayel regained its color, and his eyes returned to their normal yellow hue.
It took Nyssi a moment to understand what had happened. They all knew that Kayel possessed strange shadow powers. He used them rarely, as most people considered them impious and rather frightening. But Nyssi didn't know that Kayel could use these powers in the dark. And, judging by his behavior, Kayel seemed surprised as well.
"Are you all right?" Nyssi couldn't help but ask.
"Yup, I'm fine. I killed something. It'll be better in a minute." Kayel examined his work, while Tenuk made his way to land next to him, regaining his normal Spast form.
Now that the creature was no longer moving, they could better see what it was. Its skin was black as coal and slimy, but the saliva continued to cling to its body. It had four wings and four limbs, all ending in long claws, and two straight horns emerged from its skull.
Before Tenuk and Kayel could ask what that thing was, something howled and launched itself from a nearby bush. However, the beast had no time to reach them, as a familiar vehicle crashed into its side, flinging it at Nyssi's feet. Taking no chances, she grabbed her rifle and immediately shot it in the head, killing the creature on the spot.
"Oops...", muttered Retvik from the driver's seat, before clumsily turning off the engine and jumping out of the truck. "I, uh, didn't mean to do that. Are you two okay?"
"you almost missed all the action," regretted Tenuk. "Where were you?"
"You all left me behind. I came here as fast as I could," sighed Retvik. "Can anyone tell me what these vile creatures are?"
Retvik's question fortunately received an answer from Thassalin, who had just gotten up. He was all cut and scratched everywhere and seemed a bit disoriented, but he didn't look too badly hurt.
"YOU HAVE KILLED THE CORRUPTIIDS! THE INFECTED MONSTERS. CREATURES LEFT HERE WHEN THE CORRUPTION ATTACKED YOUR GODS."
"Are you saying... the horrible god-monster that we helped kill?", stammered Tenuk.
"YES. COMPLETELY. THERE MAY BE MORE, BUT I DIDN'T MANAGE TO AIM AT THEIR HEADS. I'M LACKING A RIFLE. PLUS, TWO AGAINST ONE, THAT'S NOT FAIR, IS IT?" Thassalin walked toward Kayel and patted his head. "THANK YOU, LITTLE ONE. YOU REMIND ME OF MY OLD FRIEND ARKADIN. BUT LESS KILLER AND LESS ABLE TO KILL UNIVERSES."
"Um... thanks... I guess," said Kayel with a shrug. "So, are we done here?"
Nyssi shrugged, then grabbed her camera to photograph the beasts, now certainly dead. She then pulled out her favorite dagger, the god of death's blade, and began cutting off one of the creature's horns, then moving on to the other. But as she finished, the creatures caught fire and quickly turned into piles of ash. The same thing happened to the horns Nyssi had cut off.
"Eh bien... c'est à la fois commode et pas commode du tout", soupira-t-elle. "Au moins, il me reste les photos..."  
